{
  "id": "c0c0c0c0-0051-0000-0000-000000000000",
  "name": "JSON AST as Canonical Code Representation",
  "type": "871ae771-b9b1-4f40-8c7f-d9038bfb69c3",
  "created": 1739692800000,
  "modified": 1775756671539,
  "content": {
    "description": [
      ":doc",
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "Status:"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " Implemented (Feb 2026). Compact JSON AST is now the canonical storage and evaluation format. The field is "
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "content.hob"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " (JSON array), not "
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "content.code"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " as originally proposed. Phase 1 (storage migration) and Phase 2 (direct evaluator dispatch) are both complete. See the implementation details below as historical context for the design decisions."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h2",
        {
          "s": "Summary"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "Replace text-based Hob source code ("
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "content.hob"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": ") with a compact JSON AST ("
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "content.code"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": ") as the canonical representation for code items. Comments are stored in a sibling property ("
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "content.comments"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": "). A thin sugar layer and pretty printer provide s-expression syntax for human interaction, but neither is load-bearing — the system operates on JSON throughout."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h2",
        {
          "s": "Motivation"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "Currently, Hob code is stored as text in "
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "content.hob"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": ". The interpreter's reader parses this text into an internal AST (typed wrapper objects like "
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "{ type: 'symbol', value: 'foo' }"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": ") before evaluation. This means:"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":ul",
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            {
              "s": "The system contains a ~200+ line recursive descent parser with escape handling, reader macros, and error recovery."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            {
              "s": "The parser is on the critical path — every code evaluation begins with a parse step."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            {
              "s": "Code is stored in a format (text) that is opaque to the rest of Hobson. Querying, indexing, or transforming code requires parsing it first."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            {
              "s": "The structural editor (if built) must parse on load and serialize on save, introducing round-trip fidelity concerns."
            }
          ]
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "The Hobson philosophy is that everything is an item and items are JSON. Code stored as text is the one exception. This proposal eliminates that exception."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h2",
        {
          "s": "Compact JSON AST Format"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "The representation maps Hob's types directly onto JSON's native types, tagging only what is ambiguous."
        }
      ],
