      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "Design Rationale"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "Symbols are the most common node type in code. By making them bare JSON strings (zero overhead), the representation is maximally compact for the common case. String literals are relatively rare in typical code and bear the small cost of a wrapper object. Keywords and item references are distinguished by prefix convention on the string, avoiding additional wrapper objects."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "Vectors and maps require wrappers because JSON arrays are already used for lists. The wrapper key is a single character ("
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "\"v\""
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": ", "
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "\"m\""
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": ") to minimize overhead."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "Examples"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "`(+ 1 (* 2 3))`"
          }
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":code-block",
        {
          "s": "[\"+\", 1, [\"*\", 2, 3]]"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "`(defn greet [name] (str \"Hello, \" name))`"
          }
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":code-block",
        {
          "s": "[\"defn\", \"greet\", {\"v\": [\"name\"]},\n  [\"str\", {\"s\": \"Hello, \"}, \"name\"]]"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "`(def config {:title \"My App\" :version 1})`"
          }
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":code-block",
        {
          "s": "[\"def\", \"config\",\n  {\"m\": [[\":title\", {\"s\": \"My App\"}], [\":version\", 1]]}]"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "`(get-field @my-note :title)`"
          }
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":code-block",
        {
          "s": "[\"get-field\", \"@my-note\", \":title\"]"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "Special Forms"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "Quoting, quasiquoting, and unquoting are represented as explicit list forms rather than reader syntax:"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":table",
        [
          ":thead",
          [
            ":tr",
            [
              ":th",
              {
                "s": "Syntax"
              }
            ],
            [
              ":th",
              {
                "s": "JSON Representation"
              }
            ]
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":tbody",
          [
            ":tr",
            [
              ":td",
              [
                ":code",
                {
                  "s": "'x"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              ":td",
              [
                ":code",
                {
                  "s": "[\"quote\", \"x\"]"
                }
              ]
            ]
          ],
          [
            ":tr",
            [
              ":td",
              {
                "s": "`"
              },
              [
                ":code",
                {
                  "s": " "
                }
              ],
              {
                "s": "(a ~b)``"
              }
            ],
            [
              ":td",
              [
                ":code",
                {
                  "s": "[\"quasiquote\", [\"a\", [\"unquote\", \"b\"]]]"
                }
              ]
            ]
          ],
          [
            ":tr",
            [
              ":td",
              [
                ":code",
                {
                  "s": "~@xs"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              ":td",
              [
                ":code",
                {
                  "s": "[\"splice-unquote\", \"xs\"]"
                }
              ]
            ]
          ]
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "This eliminates the need for reader macros in the representation. The sugar layer converts the shorthand syntax to these forms on input; the pretty printer converts back on output."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h2",
        {
          "s": "Comment Storage"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "Comments are stored as a sibling property alongside the code, keyed by path into the AST."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "Item Structure"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":code-block",
        {
          "s": "{\n  \"content\": {\n    \"code\": [\"defn\", \"add\", {\"v\": [\"a\", \"b\"]}, [\"+\", \"a\", \"b\"]],\n    \"comments\": {\n      \"\": \"Arithmetic utilities\",\n      \"3\": \"sum the two arguments\"\n    }\n  }\n}"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "Path Convention"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        {
          "s": "A comment path is a dot-separated sequence of array indices locating a position in the AST:"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":ul",
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":code",
              {
                "s": "\"\""
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " — top-level comment on the entire expression"
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":code",
              {
                "s": "\"3\""
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " — before the element at index 3 of the root list"
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":code",
              {
                "s": "\"3.1\""
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " — before element at index 1 within the element at index 3"
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":code",
              {
                "s": "\"3._end\""
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " — trailing comment after the last element within element 3"
            }
          ]
        ]
      ],
      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "Properties"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":ul",
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":strong",
              {
                "s": "The AST is perfectly clean."
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " The evaluator reads "
            },
            [
              ":code",
              {
                "s": "content.code"
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " and never encounters comments."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":strong",
              {
                "s": "Macros operate on clean data."
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " They receive and return plain arrays with no comment wrappers to handle."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":strong",
              {
                "s": "Comments are metadata about code, not code themselves."
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " Storing them separately reflects this truth."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":strong",
              {
                "s": "Both editing approaches work."
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " A text sugar layer can extract and insert comments. A structural editor can display them alongside nodes. Neither requires special-casing in the AST."
            }
          ]
        ],
        [
          ":li",
          [
            ":p",
            [
              ":strong",
              {
                "s": "Comment survival across transformations."
              }
            ],
            {
              "s": " When code is modified, comments with invalidated paths can be dropped or flagged. This mirrors text-based systems where refactoring discards comments on changed code."
            }
          ]
        ]
      ],
